Player exploratory Analysis

The Premier League, is the top level of the English football league system. Contested by 20 clubs, it operates on a system of promotion and relegation with the English Football League.

The Premier League is the most-watched sports league in the world, broadcast in 212 territories to 643 million homes and a potential TV audience of 4.7 billion people.

This dataset consisits of the 974 players which participated in the 2019-2020 season

Link - https://www.kaggle.com/krishanthbarkav/english-premier-leagueepl-player-statistics?select=pl_19-20.csv

ptn<- function(x){
  x_replace_pct<-sub("%", "", x)
  x_as_numeric<-as.numeric(x_replace_pct)/100
  }
dd=d
dd$Tackle.success..=ptn(dd$Tackle.success..)
dd$Passes=as.numeric(dd$Passes)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
dd$Cross.accuracy..=ptn(dd$Cross.accuracy..)
dd$Shooting.accuracy..=ptn(dd$Shooting.accuracy..)

as the columns Saves,penalties saved,punches,high claims,catches,sweeper clearences,throwouts and goalkicks are only for goalkeepers, we can replace the NA values in these columns with 0.

dd$Goal.Kicks[is.na(dd$Goal.Kicks)]=0
dd$Throw.outs[is.na(dd$Throw.outs)]=0
dd$Sweeper.clearances[is.na(dd$Sweeper.clearances)]=0
dd$Catches[is.na(dd$Catches)]=0
dd$High.Claims[is.na(dd$High.Claims)]=0
dd$Punches[is.na(dd$Punches)]=0
dd$Penalties.saved[is.na(dd$Penalties.saved)]=0
dd$Saves[is.na(dd$Saves)]=0

For rest of the columns we will replace with the average of that column

d1=dd
for(i in 4:ncol(d1)){
  d1[is.na(d1[,i]), i] <- round(mean(d1[,i], na.rm = TRUE))
}

Hence the data is finally clean without NA values
